# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: heatmap-viz
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Cluster analysis refers to a family of algorithms and tasks rather than one specific algorithm.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] It can be achieved by various algorithms that differ significantly in their understanding of what constitutes a cluster and how to efficiently find them.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Popular notions of clusters include groups with small distances between cluster members, dense areas of the data space, intervals or particular statistical distributions.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Clustering can therefore be formulated as a multi-objective optimization problem.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The appropriate clustering algorithm and parameter settings (including parameters such as the distance function to use, a density threshold or the number of expected clusters) depend on the individual data set and intended use of the results.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Cluster analysis as such is not an automatic task, but an iterative process of knowledge discovery or interactive multi-objective optimization that involves trial and failure.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] It is often necessary to modify data preprocessing and model parameters until the result achieves the desired properties.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Besides the term *clustering*, there are a number of terms with similar meanings, including *automatic classification*, *numerical taxonomy*, *botryology* (from Greek: βότρυς 'grape'), *typological analysis*, and *community detection*.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The subtle differences are often in the use of the results: while in data mining, the resulting groups are the matter of interest, in automatic classification the resulting discriminative power is of interest.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Cluster analysis originated in anthropology by Driver and Kroeber in 1932 and introduced to psychology by Joseph Zubin in 1938 and Robert Tryon in 1939 and famously used by Cattell beginning in 1943 for trait theory classification in personality psychology.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The notion of a "cluster" cannot be precisely defined, which is one of the reasons why there are so many clustering algorithms.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] There is a common denominator: a group of data objects.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] However, different researchers employ different cluster models, and for each of these cluster models again different algorithms can be given.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The notion of a cluster, as found by different algorithms, varies significantly in its properties.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Understanding these "cluster models" is key to understanding the differences between the various algorithms.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] A "clustering" is essentially a set of such clusters, usually containing all objects in the data set.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Additionally, it may specify the relationship of the clusters to each other, for example, a hierarchy of clusters embedded in each other.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] As listed above, clustering algorithms can be categorized based on their cluster model.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The following overview will only list the most prominent examples of clustering algorithms, as there are possibly over 100 published clustering algorithms.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Not all provide models for their clusters and can thus not easily be categorized.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] An overview of algorithms explained in Wikipedia can be found in the list of statistics algorithms.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The most appropriate clustering algorithm for a particular problem often needs to be chosen experimentally, unless there is a mathematical reason to prefer one cluster model over another.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] An algorithm that is designed for one kind of model will generally fail on a data set that contains a radically different kind of model.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] For example, k-means cannot find non-convex clusters.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Most traditional clustering methods assume the clusters exhibit a spherical, elliptical or convex shape.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Connectivity-based clustering, also known as hierarchical clustering, is based on the idea that objects are more related to nearby objects than to those farther away.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] These algorithms form clusters by connecting objects based on their distance.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] A cluster can be understood in terms of the maximum distance required to connect its elements.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] At different distance thresholds, different cluster groupings appear.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] These groupings can be visualized using a dendrogram, a tree-like diagram that shows how clusters merge as the distance increases.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] This explains the term "hierarchical clustering": instead of producing a single partition of the data set, the algorithm builds a hierarchy of clusters that merge at different distances.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] In a dendrogram, the y-axis shows the distance at which clusters merge, while the x-axis arranges objects so that clusters appear as continuous branches.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Connectivity-based clustering is a family of methods that differ in how distances between clusters are computed.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] In addition to choosing a distance function, the user must also select a **linkage criterion**, which determines how the distance between clusters is calculated.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Common linkage criteria include single-linkage clustering (minimum distance between points), complete linkage clustering (maximum distance), and UPGMA or WPGMA (average linkage based on mean distances).
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Hierarchical clustering can be either agglomerative (starting with individual elements and merging them) or divisive (starting with the full data set and splitting it).
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Identify the two closest clusters based on a chosen distance measure.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Recalculate distances between the new cluster and the remaining clusters using the selected linkage criterion.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Repeat until all data points are merged into a single cluster.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] This process produces a full hierarchy of possible clusterings rather than a single final result.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] A specific clustering can be obtained by selecting a cut level in the dendrogram, which determines how many clusters are formed.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] These methods do not produce a unique partitioning of the data set, but rather a hierarchy from which the user must choose appropriate clusters.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] They are also sensitive to outliers, which may appear as separate clusters or cause other clusters to merge.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] This effect, especially in single-linkage clustering, is known as the "chaining phenomenon".
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] In the general case, the complexity is ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{3})$ for agglomerative clustering and ${\mathcal {O}}(2^{n-1})$ for divisive clustering, which makes them computationally expensive for large data sets.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] For some special cases, more efficient methods (with complexity ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{2})$ ) are known, such as SLINK for single-linkage and CLINK for complete-linkage clustering.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] In centroid-based clustering, each cluster is represented by a central vector, which is not necessarily a member of the data set.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] When the number of clusters is fixed to *k*, *k*-means clustering gives a formal definition as an optimization problem: find the *k* cluster centers and assign the objects to the nearest cluster center, such that the squared distances from the cluster are minimized.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The optimization problem itself is known to be NP-hard, and thus the common approach is to search only for approximate solutions.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] A particularly well-known approximate method is Lloyd's algorithm, often just referred to as "*k-means algorithm*" (although another algorithm introduced this name).
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] It does however only find a local optimum, and is commonly run multiple times with different random initializations.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Most *k*-means-type algorithms require the number of clusters – *k* – to be specified in advance, which is considered to be one of the biggest drawbacks of these algorithms.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Furthermore, the algorithms prefer clusters of approximately similar size, as they will always assign an object to the nearest centroid; often yielding improperly cut borders of clusters.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] This happens primarily because the algorithm optimizes cluster centers, not cluster borders.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Assign each observation to the centroid to which it has the smallest squared Euclidean distance.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] This results in *k* distinct groups, each containing unique observations.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Recalculate centroids (see *k*-means clustering).
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Exit *iff* the new centroids are equivalent to the previous iteration's centroids.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Else, repeat the algorithm, the centroids have yet to converge.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] K-means has a number of interesting theoretical properties.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] First, it partitions the data space into a structure known as a Voronoi diagram.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Second, it is conceptually close to nearest neighbor classification, and as such is popular in machine learning.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Third, it can be seen as a variation of model-based clustering, and Lloyd's algorithm as a variation of the Expectation-maximization algorithm for this model discussed below.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The following pseudocode describes the standard iterative refinement form of *k*-means.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The algorithm alternates between an **assignment step**, which labels each point by its nearest centroid, and an **update step**, which recomputes each centroid as the mean of its assigned points.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Convergence is guaranteed in a finite number of iterations, though the result may be a local optimum.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Centroid-based clustering problems such as *k*-means and *k*-medoids are special cases of the uncapacitated, metric facility location problem, a canonical problem in the operations research and computational geometry communities.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] In a basic facility location problem (of which there are numerous variants that model more elaborate settings), the task is to find the best warehouse locations to optimally service a given set of consumers.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] One may view "warehouses" as cluster centroids and "consumer locations" as the data to be clustered.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] This makes it possible to apply the well-developed algorithmic solutions from the facility location literature to the presently considered centroid-based clustering problem.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The clustering framework most closely related to statistics is model-based clustering, which is based on distribution models.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] This approach models the data as arising from a mixture of probability distributions.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] It has the advantages of providing principled statistical answers to questions such as how many clusters there are, what clustering method or model to use, and how to detect and deal with outliers.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] While the theoretical foundation of these methods is excellent, they suffer from overfitting unless constraints are put on the model complexity.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] A more complex model will usually be able to explain the data better, which makes choosing the appropriate model complexity inherently difficult.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Standard model-based clustering methods include more parsimonious models based on the eigenvalue decomposition of the covariance matrices, that provide a balance between overfitting and fidelity to the data.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] One prominent method is known as Gaussian mixture models (using the expectation-maximization algorithm).
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Here, the data set is usually modeled with a fixed (to avoid overfitting) number of Gaussian distributions that are initialized randomly and whose parameters are iteratively optimized to better fit the data set.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] This will converge to a local optimum, so multiple runs may produce different results.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] In order to obtain a hard clustering, objects are often then assigned to the Gaussian distribution they most likely belong to; for soft clusterings, this is not necessary.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Distribution-based clustering produces complex models for clusters that can capture correlation and dependence between attributes.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] However, these algorithms put an extra burden on the user: for many real data sets, there may be no concisely defined mathematical model (e.g. assuming Gaussian distributions is a rather strong assumption on the data).
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] In density-based clustering, clusters are defined as areas of higher density than the remainder of the data set.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Objects in sparse areas – that are required to separate clusters – are usually considered to be noise and border points.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The most popular density-based clustering method is DBSCAN.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] In contrast to many newer methods, it features a well-defined cluster model called "density-reachability".
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Similar to linkage-based clustering, it is based on connecting points within certain distance thresholds.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] However, it only connects points that satisfy a density criterion, in the original variant defined as a minimum number of other objects within this radius.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] A cluster consists of all density-connected objects (which can form a cluster of an arbitrary shape, in contrast to many other methods) plus all objects that are within these objects' range.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] OPTICS is a generalization of DBSCAN that removes the need to choose an appropriate value for the range parameter $\varepsilon$ , and produces a hierarchical result related to that of linkage clustering.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] DeLi-Clu, Density-Link-Clustering combines ideas from single-linkage clustering and OPTICS, eliminating the $\varepsilon$ parameter entirely and offering performance improvements over OPTICS by using an R-tree index.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] HDBSCAN extends DBSCAN by converting it into a hierarchical clustering algorithm, and then using a technique to extract a flat clustering based in the stability of clusters.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The key drawback of DBSCAN and OPTICS is that they expect some kind of density drop to detect cluster borders.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] On data sets with, for example, overlapping Gaussian distributions – a common use case in artificial data – the cluster borders produced by these algorithms will often look arbitrary, because the cluster density decreases continuously.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] On a data set consisting of mixtures of Gaussians, these algorithms are nearly always outperformed by methods such as EM clustering that are able to precisely model this kind of data.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Mean-shift is a clustering approach where each object is moved to the densest area in its vicinity, based on kernel density estimation.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Eventually, objects converge to local maxima of density.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Similar to k-means clustering, these "density attractors" can serve as representatives for the data set, but mean-shift can detect arbitrary-shaped clusters similar to DBSCAN.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Due to the expensive iterative procedure and density estimation, mean-shift is usually slower than DBSCAN or k-Means.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Besides that, the applicability of the mean-shift algorithm to multidimensional data is hindered by the unsmooth behaviour of the kernel density estimate, which results in over-fragmentation of cluster tails.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The grid-based technique is used for a multi-dimensional data set.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] In this technique, we create a grid structure, and the comparison is performed on grids (also known as cells).
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The grid-based technique is fast and has low computational complexity.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] There are two types of grid-based clustering methods: STING and CLIQUE.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Randomly select a cell ‘c’, where c should not be traversed beforehand.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Calculate the density of all the neighbors of ‘c’.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] If the density of a neighboring cell is greater than threshold density then, add the cell in the cluster and repeat steps 4.2 and 4.3 till there is no neighbor with a density greater than threshold density.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Repeat steps 2, 3, and 4 till all the cells are traversed.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] With the increasing need to process Big data, the willingness to trade semantic meaning of the generated clusters for performance becomes more relevant.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Therefore, efforts have been put into improving the performance of existing algorithms.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] This led to the development of pre-clustering methods such as canopy clustering, which can process huge data sets efficiently, but the resulting "clusters" are merely a rough pre-partitioning of the data set to then analyze the partitions with existing slower methods such as k-means clustering.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] For high-dimensional data, many methods fail due to the curse of dimensionality, which renders particular distance functions problematic in high-dimensional spaces.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Examples for such clustering algorithms are CLIQUE and SUBCLU.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Several different clustering systems based on mutual information have been proposed.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] One is Marina Meilă's *variation of information* metric; another provides hierarchical clustering.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Using genetic algorithms, a wide range of different fit-functions can be optimized, including mutual information.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Also belief propagation, a recent development in computer science and statistical physics, has led to the creation of new types of clustering algorithms.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Evaluation (or "validation") of clustering results is as difficult as the clustering itself.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Internal evaluation measures suffer from the problem that they represent functions that themselves can be seen as a clustering objective.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] For example, one could cluster the data set by the Silhouette coefficient; except that there is no known efficient algorithm for this.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] By using such an internal measure for evaluation, one rather compares the similarity of the optimization problems, and not necessarily how useful the clustering is.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] External evaluation has similar problems: if we have such "ground truth" labels, then we would not need to cluster; and in practical applications we usually do not have such labels.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] On the other hand, the labels only reflect one possible partitioning of the data set, which does not imply that there does not exist a different, and maybe even better, clustering.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Neither of these approaches can therefore ultimately judge the actual quality of a clustering, but this needs human evaluation, which is highly subjective.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Nevertheless, such statistics can be quite informative in identifying bad clusterings, but one should not dismiss subjective human evaluation.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] When a clustering result is evaluated based on the data that was clustered itself, this is called internal evaluation.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] These methods usually assign the best score to the algorithm that produces clusters with high similarity within a cluster and low similarity between clusters.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] One drawback of using internal criteria in cluster evaluation is that high scores on an internal measure do not necessarily result in effective information retrieval applications.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Additionally, this evaluation is biased towards algorithms that use the same cluster model.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] For example, k-means clustering naturally optimizes object distances, and a distance-based internal criterion will likely overrate the resulting clustering.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Therefore, the internal evaluation measures are best suited to get some insight into situations where one algorithm performs better than another, but this shall not imply that one algorithm produces more valid results than another.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Validity as measured by such an index depends on the claim that this kind of structure exists in the data set.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] An algorithm designed for some kind of models has no chance if the data set contains a radically different set of models, or if the evaluation measures a radically different criterion.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] For example, k-means clustering can only find convex clusters, and many evaluation indexes assume convex clusters.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] On a data set with non-convex clusters neither the use of *k*-means, nor of an evaluation criterion that assumes convexity, is sound.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Many internal evaluation measures are based on the intuition that items in the same cluster should be more similar than items in different clusters.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The Dunn index aims to identify dense and well-separated clusters.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] It is defined as the ratio between the minimal inter-cluster distance to maximal intra-cluster distance.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] where *d*(*i*,*j*) represents the distance between clusters *i* and *j*, and *d* '(*k*) measures the intra-cluster distance of cluster *k*.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The inter-cluster distance *d*(*i*,*j*) between two clusters may be any number of distance measures, such as the distance between the centroids of the clusters.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Similarly, the intra-cluster distance *d* '(*k*) may be measured in a variety of ways, such as the maximal distance between any pair of elements in cluster *k*.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Since internal criterion seek clusters with high intra-cluster similarity and low inter-cluster similarity, algorithms that produce clusters with high Dunn index are more desirable.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The silhouette coefficient contrasts the average distance to elements in the same cluster with the average distance to elements in other clusters.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Objects with a high silhouette value are considered well clustered, objects with a low value may be outliers.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] This index works well with *k*-means clustering, and is also used to determine the optimal number of clusters.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] This matrix consider pairs of objects: the distance between the pair as a scoring function and the partition pairs defined true positive, true negatives, false negatives and true negatives by considering if pairs are in the same clusters of not.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] This index borrow the same characteristics as the AUC in the supervised scenario including an expected value of 0.5 and vizualisation of results.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] In external evaluation, clustering results are evaluated based on data that was not used for clustering, such as known class labels and external benchmarks.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Such benchmarks consist of a set of pre-classified items, and these sets are often created by (expert) humans.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Thus, the benchmark sets can be thought of as a gold standard for evaluation.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] These types of evaluation methods measure how close the clustering is to the predetermined benchmark classes.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] However, it has recently been discussed whether this is adequate for real data, or only on synthetic data sets with a factual ground truth, since classes can contain internal structure, the attributes present may not allow separation of clusters or the classes may contain anomalies.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Additionally, from a knowledge discovery point of view, the reproduction of known knowledge may not necessarily be the intended result.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] In the special scenario of constrained clustering, where meta information (such as class labels) is used already in the clustering process, the hold-out of information for evaluation purposes is non-trivial.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] A number of measures are adapted from variants used to evaluate classification tasks.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] In place of counting the number of times a class was correctly assigned to a single data point (known as true positives), such *pair counting* metrics assess whether each pair of data points that is truly in the same cluster is predicted to be in the same cluster.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Purity is a measure of the extent to which clusters contain a single class.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Its calculation can be thought of as follows: For each cluster, count the number of data points from the most common class in said cluster.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Now take the sum over all clusters and divide by the total number of data points.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] This measure doesn't penalize having many clusters, and more clusters will make it easier to produce a high purity.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] A purity score of 1 is always possible by putting each data point in its own cluster.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Also, purity doesn't work well for imbalanced data, where even poorly performing clustering algorithms will give a high purity value.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] For example, if a size 1000 dataset consists of two classes, one containing 999 points and the other containing 1 point, then every possible partition will have a purity of at least 99.9%.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The Rand index computes how similar the clusters (returned by the clustering algorithm) are to the benchmark classifications.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] where $TP$ is the number of true positives, $TN$ is the number of true negatives, $FP$ is the number of false positives, and $FN$ is the number of false negatives.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The instances being counted here are the number of correct *pairwise* assignments.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] That is, $TP$ is the number of pairs of points that are clustered together in the predicted partition and in the ground truth partition, $FP$ is the number of pairs of points that are clustered together in the predicted partition but not in the ground truth partition etc.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] If the dataset is of size N, then $TP+TN+FP+FN={\binom {N}{2}}$ .
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] One issue with the Rand index is that false positives and false negatives are equally weighted.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] This may be an undesirable characteristic for some clustering applications.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The F-measure addresses this concern, as does the chance-corrected adjusted Rand index.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The F-measure can be used to balance the contribution of false negatives by weighting recall through a parameter $\beta \geq 0$ .
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Let **precision** and **recall** (both external evaluation measures in themselves) be defined as follows: $P={\frac {TP}{TP+FP}}$ $R={\frac {TP}{TP+FN}}$ where P is the precision rate and R is the recall rate.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] In other words, recall has no impact on the F-measure when $\beta =0$ , and increasing $\beta$ allocates an increasing amount of weight to recall in the final F-measure.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Also $TN$ is not taken into account and can vary from 0 upward without bound.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The Jaccard index is used to quantify the similarity between two datasets.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The Jaccard index takes on a value between 0 and 1.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] An index of 1 means that the two dataset are identical, and an index of 0 indicates that the datasets have no common elements.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The Jaccard index is defined by the following formula: $J(A,B)={\frac {|A\cap B|}{|A\cup B|}}={\frac {TP}{TP+FP+FN}}$ This is simply the number of unique elements common to both sets divided by the total number of unique elements in both sets.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Note that $TN$ is not taken into account.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The Dice symmetric measure doubles the weight on $TP$ while still ignoring $TN$ : $DSC={\frac {2TP}{2TP+FP+FN}}$ .
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The Fowlkes–Mallows index computes the similarity between the clusters returned by the clustering algorithm and the benchmark classifications.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The higher the value of the Fowlkes–Mallows index the more similar the clusters and the benchmark classifications are.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] It can be computed using the following formula: $FM={\sqrt {{\frac {TP}{TP+FP}}\cdot {\frac {TP}{TP+FN}}}}$ where $TP$ is the number of true positives, $FP$ is the number of false positives, and $FN$ is the number of false negatives.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The $FM$ index is the geometric mean of the precision and recall P and R , and is thus also known as the G-measure, while the F-measure is their harmonic mean.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Moreover, precision and recall are also known as Wallace's indices $B^{I}$ and $B^{II}$ .
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Chance normalized versions of recall, precision and G-measure correspond to Informedness, Markedness and Matthews Correlation and relate strongly to Kappa.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The Chi index is an external validation index that measure the clustering results by applying the chi-squared statistic.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] This index scores positively the fact that the labels are as sparse as possible across the clusters, i.e., that each cluster has as few different labels as possible.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The higher the value of the Chi Index the greater the relationship between the resulting clusters and the label used.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The mutual information is an information theoretic measure of how much information is shared between a clustering and a ground-truth classification that can detect a non-linear similarity between two clustering.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Normalized mutual information is a family of corrected-for-chance variants of this that has a reduced bias for varying cluster numbers.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] A confusion matrix can be used to quickly visualize the results of a classification (or clustering) algorithm.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] It shows how different a cluster is from the gold standard cluster.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] To measure cluster tendency is to measure to what degree clusters exist in the data to be clustered, and may be performed as an initial test, before attempting clustering.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] One way to do this is to compare the data against random data.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] On average, random data should not have clusters .
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] uniformly randomly distributed data points.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] With this definition, uniform random data should tend to have values near to 0.5, and clustered data should tend to have values nearer to 1.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] , making this statistic largely useless in application (as real data never is remotely uniform).
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] As clustering algorithms are increasingly deployed by corporations and governmental organizations to categorize populations and automate decisions with real world data, concerns regarding algorithmic bias have become more prevalent.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Because clustering is a form of unsupervised learning, it identifies patterns within existing data.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Consequently, these models can inadvertently reinforce historical inequalities already existent in the training datasets.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] In response, researchers have developed "Fair Clustering" frameworks, such as the Fairlet approach, which ensures that each cluster maintains a balanced representation of protected groups relative to the overall population.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Under the legal doctrine of disparate impact, a process is considered discriminatory if it results in disproportionately adverse outcomes for a protected class, even if the algorithm is facially neutral (i.e., it does not explicitly use attributes like race or gender).
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Unfairness often occurs through proxy variables.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] For instance, even if a dataset is stripped of race, a clustering algorithm might use ZIP codes or educational background as features.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] Because these variables are often highly related to economic status and ethnicity, the resulting clusters will effectively segregate individuals by these characteristics.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p01] The application of clustering in predictive policing has demonstrated how historical bias in data can create feedback loops.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p02] Cluster analysis is used for data analysis across a wide range of fields.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p02] In the natural sciences, techniques such as hierarchical clustering, *k*-means,dimensionality reduction, principal component analysis (PCA), and t-SNE are frequently used to make sense of the dense data.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p02] In computing and technology applications, clustering is the driving force behind machine learning's unsupervised learning, and is embedded in systems ranging from search engines to recommendation platforms.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p02] Common algorithms in this field include *k*-means, DBSCAN, mean shift, and spectral clustering, often applied after feature extraction or embedding, which are steps that map raw data, such as text, images, sensor logs, into a vector space amenable to distance based grouping.
[src:heatmap-viz/cluster-analysis-p02] In business and the social sciences, clustering is most often applied to tabular survey and transaction data, where the aim is to segment populations into consumer groups, create detailed market analysis insights, or illustrate voter preferences.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] In statistics, a **contingency table** (also known as a **cross tabulation** or **crosstab**) is a type of table in a matrix format that displays the multivariate frequency distribution of the variables.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] They are heavily used in survey research, business intelligence, engineering, and scientific research.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] They provide a basic picture of the interrelation between two variables and can help find interactions between them.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] The term *contingency table* was first used by Karl Pearson in "On the Theory of Contingency and Its Relation to Association and Normal Correlation", part of the *Drapers' Company Research Memoirs Biometric Series I* published in 1904.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] A crucial problem of multivariate statistics is finding the (direct-)dependence structure underlying the variables contained in high-dimensional contingency tables.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] If some of the conditional independences are revealed, then even the storage of the data can be done in a smarter way (see Lauritzen (2002)).
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] In order to do this one can use information theory concepts, which gain the information only from the distribution of probability, which can be expressed easily from the contingency table by the relative frequencies.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] A pivot table is a way to create contingency tables using spreadsheet software.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] Suppose there are two variables, sex (male or female) and handedness (right- or left-handed).
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] Further suppose that 100 individuals are randomly sampled from a very large population as part of a study of sex differences in handedness.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] A contingency table can be created to display the numbers of individuals who are male right-handed and left-handed, female right-handed and left-handed.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] Such a contingency table is shown below.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] The numbers of the males, females, and right- and left-handed individuals are called marginal totals.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] The grand total (the total number of individuals represented in the contingency table) is the number in the bottom right corner.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] The table allows users to see at a glance that the proportion of men who are right-handed is about the same as the proportion of women who are right-handed although the proportions are not identical.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] The strength of the association can be measured by the odds ratio, and the population odds ratio estimated by the sample odds ratio.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] If the proportions of individuals in the different columns vary significantly between rows (or vice versa), it is said that there is a *contingency* between the two variables.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] In other words, the two variables are *not* independent.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] If there is no contingency, it is said that the two variables are *independent*.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] The example above is the simplest kind of contingency table, a table in which each variable has only two levels; this is called a 2 × 2 contingency table.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] In principle, any number of rows and columns may be used.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] There may also be more than two variables, but higher order contingency tables are difficult to represent visually.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] The relation between ordinal variables, or between ordinal and categorical variables, may also be represented in contingency tables, although such a practice is rare.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] For more on the use of a contingency table for the relation between two ordinal variables, see Goodman and Kruskal's gamma.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] The degree of association between the two variables can be assessed by a number of coefficients.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] The following subsections describe a few of them.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] For a more complete discussion of their uses, see the main articles linked under each subsection heading.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] The simplest measure of association for a 2 × 2 contingency table is the odds ratio.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] Given two events, A and B, the odds ratio is defined as the ratio of the odds of A in the presence of B and the odds of A in the absence of B, or equivalently (due to symmetry), the ratio of the odds of B in the presence of A and the odds of B in the absence of A.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] Two events are independent if and only if the odds ratio is 1; if the odds ratio is greater than 1, the events are positively associated; if the odds ratio is less than 1, the events are negatively associated.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] Then its sign equals the sign of the product of the main diagonal elements of the table minus the product of the off–diagonal elements. φ takes on the minimum value −1.0 or the maximum value of +1.0 if and only if every marginal proportion is equal to 0.5 (and two diagonal cells are empty).
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] Two alternatives are the *contingency coefficient* *C*, and Cramér's V.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] Another choice is the tetrachoric correlation coefficient but it is only applicable to 2 × 2 tables.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] Polychoric correlation is an extension of the tetrachoric correlation to tables involving variables with more than two levels.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] Tetrachoric correlation assumes that the variable underlying each dichotomous measure is normally distributed.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] The tetrachoric correlation coefficient should not be confused with the Pearson correlation coefficient computed by assigning, say, values 0.0 and 1.0 to represent the two levels of each variable (which is mathematically equivalent to the φ coefficient).
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] The lambda coefficient is a measure of the strength of association of the cross tabulations when the variables are measured at the nominal level.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] Values range from 0.0 (no association) to 1.0 (the maximum possible association).
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] Asymmetric lambda measures the percentage improvement in predicting the dependent variable.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] Symmetric lambda measures the percentage improvement when prediction is done in both directions.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] The uncertainty coefficient, or Theil's U, is another measure for variables at the nominal level.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] Its values range from −1.0 (100% negative association, or perfect inversion) to +1.0 (100% positive association, or perfect agreement).
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] A value of 0.0 indicates the absence of association.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] This asymmetrical property can lead to insights not as evident in symmetrical measures of association.
[src:heatmap-viz/contingency-table] Gamma, Tau-b and Tau-c are used when the categories or levels of both variables have a natural order.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] In statistics, **correlation** is a type of statistical relationship between two random variables or bivariate data.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] It usually refers to the extent to which a pair of quantities are linearly related.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] More generally, an arbitrary relationship between variables is called an **association**, meaning the degree to which the variability in one can be accounted for by the other.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] The presence of a correlation is not sufficient to infer the presence of a causal relationship, and this is often stated as "correlation does not imply causation".
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Furthermore, the concept of correlation is not the same as dependence: if two variables are independent, then they are uncorrelated, but the opposite is not necessarily true – even if two variables are uncorrelated, they might be dependent on each other.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Correlations are useful because they can indicate a predictive relationship that can be exploited in practice.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] For example, an electrical utility may produce less power on a mild day based on the correlation between electricity demand and weather.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] In this example, there is a causal relationship, because extreme weather causes people to use more electricity for heating or cooling.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] There are several correlation coefficients that may be used to measure correlation, often denoted $\rho$ or r .
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] The most common of these is the **Pearson correlation coefficient**, which is sensitive only to a linear relationship between two variables (which in turn may be present even when one variable is a nonlinear function of the other).
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Other correlation coefficients, such as **Spearman's rank correlation coefficient**, have been developed to be more robust than Pearson's and to detect less structured relationships between variables.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] The concept has been generalized to other forms of association between two variables, such as mutual information and distance covariance.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] The most familiar measure of dependence between two quantities is the Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient, most commonly called 'Pearson's correlation coefficient' or simply 'the correlation coefficient' (as it is the most common variant).
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] It is obtained by taking the ratio of the covariance between two variables of a numerical dataset normalized to the square root of their variances.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Equivalently, Pearson's correlation coefficient can be calculated by dividing the covariance of the two variables by the product of their standard deviations.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Karl Pearson developed the coefficient from a similar idea by Francis Galton.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] A Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient attempts to establish a line of best fit through a dataset of two variables by essentially laying out the expected values and the resulting Pearson's correlation coefficient indicates how far away the actual dataset is from the expected values.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Depending on the sign of the Pearson's correlation coefficient, the result can be either a negative or positive correlation if there is any sort of relationship between the variables in the data set.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] where $\operatorname {E}$ is the expected value operator, $\operatorname {cov}$ means covariance, and $\operatorname {corr}$ is a widely used alternative notation for the correlation coefficient.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] The Pearson correlation is defined only if both standard deviations are finite and positive.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] It is a corollary of the Cauchy–Schwarz inequality that the absolute value of the Pearson correlation coefficient is not bigger than 1.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Therefore, the value of a correlation coefficient ranges between −1 and +1.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] As it approaches zero there is less of a relationship (closer to uncorrelated).
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] The closer the coefficient is to either −1 or 1, the stronger the correlation between the variables.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] If the variables are independent, Pearson's correlation coefficient is 0.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] However, because the correlation coefficient detects only linear dependencies between two variables, the converse is not necessarily true.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] A correlation coefficient of 0 does not imply that the variables are independent.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] For example, suppose the random variable X is symmetrically distributed about zero, and $Y=X^{2}$ .
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Then Y is completely determined by X , so that X and Y are perfectly dependent, but their correlation is zero; they are uncorrelated.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] However, in the special case when X and Y are jointly normal, uncorrelatedness is equivalent to independence.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Even though uncorrelated data does not necessarily imply independence, one can check if random variables are independent if their mutual information is 0.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Given a series of n measurements of the pair $(X_{i},Y_{i})$ indexed by $i=1,\ldots ,n$ , the *sample correlation coefficient* can be used to estimate the population Pearson correlation $\rho _{X,Y}$ between X and Y .
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] where ${\overline {x}}$ and ${\overline {y}}$ are the sample means of X and Y , and $s_{x}$ and $s_{y}$ are the corrected sample standard deviations of X and Y .
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] where $s'_{x}$ and $s'_{y}$ are the *uncorrected* sample standard deviations of X and Y .
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] If x and y are results of measurements that contain measurement error, the realistic limits on the correlation coefficient are not −1 to +1 but a smaller range.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] For the case of a linear model with a single independent variable, the coefficient of determination (R squared) is the square of $r_{xy}$ , Pearson's product-moment coefficient.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Consider the joint probability distribution of X and Y given in the table below.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Rank correlation coefficients, such as Spearman's rank correlation coefficient and Kendall's rank correlation coefficient (τ) measure the extent to which, as one variable increases, the other variable tends to increase, without requiring that increase to be represented by a linear relationship.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] If, as the one variable increases, the other *decreases*, the rank correlation coefficients will be negative.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] It is common to regard these rank correlation coefficients as alternatives to Pearson's coefficient, used either to reduce the amount of calculation or to make the coefficient less sensitive to non-normality in distributions.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] As we go from each pair to the next pair, x increases, and so does y .
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] This relationship is perfect, in the sense that an increase in x is *always* accompanied by an increase in y .
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] This means that we have a perfect rank correlation, and both Spearman's and Kendall's correlation coefficients are 1, whereas in this example Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient is 0.7544, indicating that the points are far from lying on a straight line.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] In the same way if y always *decreases* when x *increases*, the rank correlation coefficients will be −1, while the Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient may or may not be close to −1, depending on how close the points are to a straight line.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Although in the extreme cases of perfect rank correlation the two coefficients are both equal (being both +1 or both −1), this is not generally the case, and so values of the two coefficients cannot meaningfully be compared.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] For example, for the three pairs (1, 1) (2, 3) (3, 2) Spearman's coefficient is 1/2, while Kendall's coefficient is 1/3.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] The conventional dictum that "correlation does not imply causation" means that correlation cannot be used by itself to infer a causal relationship between the variables.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] This dictum should not be taken to mean that correlations cannot indicate the potential existence of causal relations.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] However, the causes underlying the correlation, if any, may be indirect and unknown, and high correlations also overlap with identity relations (tautologies), where no causal process exists (e.g., between two variables measuring the same construct).
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Consequently, a correlation between two variables is not a sufficient condition to establish a causal relationship (in either direction).
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] A correlation between age and height in children is fairly causally transparent, but a correlation between mood and health in people is less so.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Does improved mood lead to improved health, or does good health lead to good mood, or both?
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Or does some other factor underlie both?
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] In other words, a correlation can be taken as evidence for a possible causal relationship, but cannot indicate what the causal relationship, if any, might be.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] The Pearson correlation coefficient indicates the strength of a *linear* relationship between two variables, but its value generally does not completely characterize their relationship.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] In particular, if the conditional mean of Y given X , denoted $\operatorname {E} (Y\mid X)$ , is not linear in X , the correlation coefficient will not fully determine the form of $\operatorname {E} (Y\mid X)$ .
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] The adjacent image shows scatter plots of Anscombe's quartet, a set of four different pairs of variables created by Francis Anscombe.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] The four y variables have the same mean (7.5), variance (4.12), correlation (0.816) and regression line ( ${\textstyle y=3+0.5x}$ ).
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] However, as can be seen on the plots, the distribution of the variables is very different.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] The first one (top left) seems to be distributed normally, and corresponds to what one would expect when considering two variables correlated and following the assumption of normality.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] The second one (top right) is not distributed normally; while an obvious relationship between the two variables can be observed, it is not linear.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] In this case the Pearson correlation coefficient does not indicate that there is an exact functional relationship: only the extent to which that relationship can be approximated by a linear relationship.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] In the third case (bottom left), the linear relationship is perfect, except for one outlier which exerts enough influence to lower the correlation coefficient from 1 to 0.816.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Finally, the fourth example (bottom right) shows another example when one outlier is enough to produce a high correlation coefficient, even though the relationship between the two variables is not linear.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] These examples indicate that the correlation coefficient, as a summary statistic, cannot replace visual examination of the data.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] The examples are sometimes said to demonstrate that the Pearson correlation assumes that the data follow a normal distribution, but this is only partially correct.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] The Pearson correlation can be accurately calculated for any distribution that has a finite covariance matrix, which includes most distributions encountered in practice.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] However, the Pearson correlation coefficient (taken together with the sample mean and variance) is only a sufficient statistic if the data is drawn from a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] As a result, the Pearson correlation coefficient fully characterizes the relationship between variables if and only if the data are drawn from a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Similarly for two stochastic processes $\left\{X_{t}\right\}_{t\in {\mathcal {T}}}$ and $\left\{Y_{t}\right\}_{t\in {\mathcal {T}}}$ : If they are independent, then they are uncorrelated.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] The opposite of this statement might not be true.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Even if two variables are uncorrelated, they might not be independent of each other.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] The degree of dependence between variables X and Y does not depend on the scale on which the variables are expressed.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] That is, if we are analyzing the relationship between X and Y, most correlation measures are unaffected by transforming X to *a* + *bX* and Y to *c* + *dY*, where *a*, *b*, *c*, and *d* are constants (*b* and *d* being positive).
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] This is true of some correlation statistics as well as their population analogues.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Some correlation statistics, such as the rank correlation coefficient, are also invariant to monotone transformations of the marginal distributions of X and/or Y.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Most correlation measures are sensitive to the manner in which X and Y are sampled.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Dependencies tend to be stronger if viewed over a wider range of values.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Several techniques have been developed that attempt to correct for range restriction in one or both variables, and are commonly used in meta-analysis; the most common are Thorndike's case II and case III equations.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Various correlation measures in use may be undefined for certain joint distributions of X and Y.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] For example, the Pearson correlation coefficient is defined in terms of moments, and hence will be undefined if the moments are undefined.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Measures of dependence based on quantiles are always defined.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Sample-based statistics intended to estimate population measures of dependence may or may not have desirable statistical properties such as being unbiased, or asymptotically consistent, based on the spatial structure of the population from which the data were sampled.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Sensitivity to the data distribution can be used to an advantage.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] For example, scaled correlation is designed to use the sensitivity to the range in order to pick out correlations between fast components of time series.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] By reducing the range of values in a controlled manner, the correlations on long time scale are filtered out and only the correlations on short time scales are revealed.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Thus the diagonal entries are all identically one.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] If the measures of correlation used are product-moment coefficients, the correlation matrix is the same as the covariance matrix of the standardized random variables $X_{i}/\sigma (X_{i})$ for $i=1,\dots ,n$ .
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] This applies both to the matrix of population correlations (in which case $\sigma$ is the population standard deviation), and to the matrix of sample correlations (in which case $\sigma$ denotes the sample standard deviation).
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Consequently, each is necessarily a positive-semidefinite matrix.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Moreover, the correlation matrix is strictly positive definite if no variable can have all its values exactly generated as a linear function of the values of the others.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] The correlation matrix is symmetric because the correlation between $X_{i}$ and $X_{j}$ is the same as the correlation between $X_{j}$ and $X_{i}$ .
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] A correlation matrix appears, for example, in one formula for the coefficient of multiple determination, a measure of goodness of fit in multiple regression.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] In statistical modelling, correlation matrices representing the relationships between variables are categorized into different correlation structures, which are distinguished by factors such as the number of parameters required to estimate them.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] For example, in an exchangeable correlation matrix, all pairs of variables are modeled as having the same correlation, so all non-diagonal elements of the matrix are equal to each other.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] On the other hand, an autoregressive matrix is often used when variables represent a time series, since correlations are likely to be greater when measurements are closer in time.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Other examples include independent, unstructured, M-dependent, and Toeplitz.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] In exploratory data analysis, the iconography of correlations consists in replacing a correlation matrix by a diagram where the "remarkable" correlations are represented by a solid line (positive correlation), or a dotted line (negative correlation).
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] In some applications (e.g., building data models from only partially observed data) one wants to find the "nearest" correlation matrix to an "approximate" correlation matrix (e.g., a matrix which typically lacks positive semi-definiteness due to the way it has been computed).
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] In 2002, Higham formalized the notion of nearness using the Frobenius norm and provided a method for computing the nearest correlation matrix using the Dykstra's projection algorithm.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] This sparked interest in the subject, with new theoretical (e.g., computing the nearest correlation matrix with factor structure) and numerical (e.g. usage of Newton's method for computing the nearest correlation matrix) results obtained in the subsequent years.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] where $\operatorname {\boldsymbol {\mathcal {E}}} (X)$ and $\operatorname {\boldsymbol {\mathcal {E}}} (Y)$ are the expected values of $\ X\$ and $\ Y\ ,$ respectively, and $\ \sigma _{X}\$ and $\ \sigma _{Y}\$ are the standard deviations of $\ X\$ and $\ Y\ ,$ respectively.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] where $\ F_{Hyp}\$ is the Gaussian hypergeometric function.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] This density is both a Bayesian posterior density and an exact optimal confidence distribution density.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] The information given by a correlation coefficient is not enough to define the dependence structure between random variables.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] The correlation coefficient completely defines the dependence structure only in very particular cases, for example when the distribution is a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] (See diagram above.) In the case of elliptical distributions it characterizes the (hyper-)ellipses of equal density; however, it does not completely characterize the dependence structure (for example, a multivariate t-distribution's degrees of freedom determine the level of tail dependence).
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] For continuous variables, multiple alternative measures of dependence were introduced to address the deficiency of Pearson's correlation that it can be zero for dependent random variables (see and references therein for an overview).
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] They all share the important property that a value of zero implies independence.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] This led some authors to recommend their routine usage, particularly of distance correlation.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Another alternative measure is the Randomized Dependence Coefficient.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] The RDC is a computationally efficient, copula-based measure of dependence between multivariate random variables and is invariant with respect to non-linear scalings of random variables.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] One important disadvantage of the alternative, more general measures is that, when used to test whether two variables are associated, they tend to have lower power compared to Pearson's correlation when the data follow a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] This is an implication of the No free lunch theorem.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] To detect all kinds of relationships, these measures have to sacrifice power on other relationships, particularly for the important special case of a linear relationship with Gaussian marginals, for which Pearson's correlation is optimal.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Another problem concerns interpretation.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] While Pearson's correlation can be interpreted for all values, the alternative measures can generally only be interpreted meaningfully at the extremes.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] For two binary variables, the odds ratio measures their dependence, and takes a range of non-negative numbers, possibly infinity: ⁠ $[0,+\infty ]$ ⁠.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] Related statistics such as Yule's *Y* and Yule's *Q* normalize this to the correlation-like range ⁠ $[-1,1]$ ⁠.
[src:heatmap-viz/correlation] The odds ratio is generalized by the logistic model to model cases where the dependent variables are discrete and there may be one or more independent variables.
[src:heatmap-viz/dendrogram] A **dendrogram** is a diagram representing a tree graph.
[src:heatmap-viz/dendrogram] The name *dendrogram* derives from the two ancient greek words δένδρον (*déndron*), meaning "tree", and γράμμα (*grámma*), meaning "drawing, mathematical figure".
[src:heatmap-viz/dendrogram] For a clustering example, suppose that five taxa ( a to e ) have been clustered by UPGMA based on a matrix of genetic distances.
[src:heatmap-viz/dendrogram] The hierarchical clustering dendrogram would show a column of five nodes representing the initial data (here individual taxa), and the remaining nodes represent the clusters to which the data belong, with the arrows representing the distance (dissimilarity).
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] A **heat map** (or **heatmap**) is a two-dimensional data visualization technique that represents the magnitude of individual values within a dataset as a color.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] The variation in color may be by hue or intensity.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] In some applications such as crime analytics or website click-tracking, color is used to represent the *density* of data points rather than a value associated with each point.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] "Heat map" is a relatively new term, but the practice of shading matrices has existed for over a century.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Heat maps originated in 2D displays of the values in a data matrix.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Larger values were represented by small dark gray or black squares (pixels) and smaller values by lighter squares.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] The earliest known example dates to 1873, when Toussaint Loua used a hand-drawn and colored shaded matrix to visualize social statistics across the districts of Paris.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] The idea of reordering rows and columns to reveal structure in a data matrix, known as seriation, was introduced by Flinders Petrie in 1899.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] In 1950, Louis Guttman developed the Scalogram, a method for ordering binary matrices to expose a one-dimensional scale structure.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] In 1957, Peter Sneath displayed the results of a cluster analysis by permuting the rows and the columns of a matrix to place similar values near each other according to the clustering.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] This idea was implemented by Robert Ling in 1973 with a computer program called SHADE.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Ling used overstruck printer characters to represent different shades of gray, one character-width per pixel.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Leland Wilkinson developed the first computer program in 1994 (SYSTAT) to produce cluster heat maps with high-resolution color graphics.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] The Eisen et al. display shown in the figure is a replication of the earlier SYSTAT design.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Software designer Cormac Kinney trademarked the term 'heat map' in 1991 to describe computer software used to display real-time financial market information.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] In 1998 the trademark was acquired by SS&C Technologies, Inc., but the company did not extend the license, so it was annulled in 2006.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] There are two primary categories of heat maps: spatial and grid.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Additionally, there are over ten various types of heat maps.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] A **spatial heat map** displays the magnitude of a spatial phenomenon as color, usually cast over a map.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] In the image labeled "Spatial Heat Map Example," temperature is displayed by color range across a map of the world.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Color ranges from blue (cold) to red (hot).
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] A **grid heat map** displays magnitude as color in a two-dimensional matrix, with each dimension representing a category of trait and the color representing the magnitude of some measurement on the combined traits from each of the two categories.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] For example, one dimension might represent year, and the other dimension might represent month, and the value measured might be temperature.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] This heat map would show how temperature changed over the years in each month.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Grid heat maps are further categorized into two different types of matrices: clustered, and correlogram.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] In a grid heat map, colors are presented in a grid of a fixed size, with every cell in the grid also being an equal size and shape.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] The goal is to detect clustering, or suggest the presence of clusters.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] A spatial heat map is often used on maps or satellite imagery (see GIS), where there is no concept of cells, and instead the colors vary continuously.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Heat maps have a wide range of possibilities amongst applications due to their ability to simplify data and make for visually appealing to read data analysis.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Many applications using different types of heat maps are listed below.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Business Analysis: Heat maps are used in business analytics to give a visual representation about a company's current functioning, performance, and the need for improvements.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Heat maps are a way to analyze a company's existing data and update it to reflect growth and other specific efforts.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Heat maps visually appeal to team members and clients of the business or company.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Websites: There are many different ways heat maps are used within websites to determine a visiting users actions.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Typically, there are multiple heat maps used together to determine insight to a website on what are the best and worst performing elements on the page.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Some specific heat maps used for website analysis are listed below.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Exploratory Data Analysis: Working with small and large data sets, data scientists and data analysts look at and determine essential relationships and characteristics amongst different points in a data set as well as features of those data points.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Data scientists and analysts work with a team of others in different professions.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] The use of heat maps make for a visually easy way to summarize findings and main components.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] There are other ways to represent data, however heat maps can visualize these data points and their relationships in a high dimensional space without becoming too compact and visually unappealing.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Heat maps in data analysis, allow for specific variables of rows and/or columns on the axes and even on the diagonal.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Biology: In the biological field, heat maps are used to visually represent large and small sets of data.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] The focus is towards patterns and similarities in DNA, RNA, gene expression, etc.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Financial Analysis: The values of different product and assets fluctuate both rapidly and/or gradually over time.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] The need to log changes to the daily markets is imperative.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] It allows for the ability to draw predictions from patterns while being able to revisit past numerical data.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Heat maps are able to remove the tedious process and enable the user to visualize data points and compare amongst the different performers.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Geographical Visualization: Heat maps are used to visualize and display a geographic distribution of data.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Heat maps represent different densities of data points on a geographical map to help users see the intensities of certain phenomena and to show items of most or least importance.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Heat maps used in geographical visualization are sometimes confused with choropleth maps, but the difference comes with how certain data is presented which differentiate the two.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Sports: Heat maps can be used in many sports and can influence manager's and/or coaches decisions based on high and low densities of data displayed.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Users can identify patterns within the game, the strategies of opponents and one's own team, make more informed decisions benefitting the player, team, and business, and can enhance performance in different areas by identifying enhancement is needed.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Heat maps also visualize comparisons and relationships amongst different teams in the same sport or between different sports all together.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Cybersecurity: In intrusion detection systems and log analysis, heat maps are used to highlight unusual access patterns, port scanning attempts, and malicious IP clustering.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] They help SOC (Security Operations Center) analysts quickly spot anomalies in large datasets.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Urban Planning: Heat maps are used in urban planning to visualize traffic congestion, pedestrian flow, and environmental conditions for data-driven infrastructure development (Batty et al., 2012).
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Environmental heat maps track air quality and urban heat islands, guiding green space planning (EEA, 2021).
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Noise pollution heat maps aid zoning and mitigation near residential areas (EEA, 2020).
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Commercial planners use foot traffic heat maps to optimize retail layouts (SmartSantander, 2014).
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Integrated in smart city systems, these maps enhance livability, sustainability, and safety (Batty et al., 2012).
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Many different color schemes can be used to illustrate the heat map, with perceptual advantages and disadvantages for each.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Choosing a good color scheme is integral to accurately and effectively displaying data, whereas a poor color scheme can lead viewers to inaccurate conclusions or exclude those with color deficiencies from proper analysis of said data.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Rainbow color maps, while a common choice, suffer from both accessibility and data continuity concerns.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Rainbow maps pose a challenge for users with color vision deficiencies, particularly in those with issues distinguishing red and green – a condition affecting a significant portion of the population.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] In addition to accessibility issues, rainbow heat map colors are not perceptually uniform; equal increments in data values do not correspond to equal changes in color.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] The lack of uniformity can create misleading visual effects, like an artificial boundary or gradient.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] These effects can compromise the accuracy of effectiveness of the visualization.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] This example of the amplitude with the colors showcasing the phase angle can be hard to interpret with the entire rainbow of colors.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] In this case, the rainbow color scheme may cloud interpretation for those with color vision deficiencies or create confusion by some of the hard color boundaries across the diagram.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] To address these challenges, perceptually uniform color sets have been created to accommodate visual impairments and maintain consistent color differences proportional to differences in data.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Perceptually uniform color schemes are carefully designed to maintain consistent perceptual differences and offer a better viewing experience for viewers with color vision deficiencies.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] When implementing these color schemes into a heat map, designers must consider the data context and intended emphasis.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] These schemes follow three main patterns: sequential gradients (varying intensity of a single hue), diverging palettes (two contrasting hues with a neutral midpoint), and qualitative sets for categorical data.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Scientific visualization has produced several perceptually uniform color sets (like Viridis, Magma, and Cividis) that address both uniformity and accessibility concerns.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Device limitations can also significantly affect heat map visualization effectiveness.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] When displayed on low-resolution screens, highly detailed color gradients may appear pixelated or banded, reducing the quality of the visualization; this is known as color quantization, which can obscure or wrongly emphasize pieces of data.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] To mitigate these effects, designers should consider all devices that will display their heat map, and their color limitations.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Comprehensive testing and using a scheme with few colors is the safest bet when creating a heat map that will be viewed across multiple device types.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Grey-scale compatibility is essential for heat map accessibility, especially when considering print media, black and white only displays, or monochromatic vision.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] When converting to grey-scale, many color schemes will lose their distinctive data mappings, allowing for different values to appear identical in luminescence.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Grey-scale friendly color schemes are designed to incorporate contrast between data points even when color is removed, such as the "virdis" family.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Choropleth maps and heat maps are often used in place of one another incorrectly when referring to data visualized geographically.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Both techniques show the proportion of a variable of interest, but the two differ in how the boundaries for the variable's data aggregations are constructed.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] If the data were collected and aggregated using irregular boundaries, such as administrative units, then a heat map displaying that data will be the same as a choropleth map, encouraging confusion about how the two differ.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Choropleth maps show data grouped by geographic boundaries like countries, states, provinces or even floodplains.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Each region has a singular value, visualized by color intensity, shading or pattern.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] The figure on the right displaying a choropleth map showing the United States' population density by state may be used as an example.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] The figure illustrates a singular value (population) denoted by blue color intensity proportionate to the state's value relative to all other states' values, bounded by each state's border.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Similarly, heat maps may also visualize data over a geographic region.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] However, unlike choropleth maps, heat maps show the proportion of a variable over an arbitrary, but usually small grid size, independent of geographic boundaries.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] The figure on the right displaying a heat map of world population is an example.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] The figure illustrates a single value (population) bounded in an arbitrary grid (square kilometers) with each cell in the grid represented by a color intensity proportionate to the value of the cell relative to all other cells.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Some heat maps that are created using approximated regional data may show familiar geographic borders in the visualization where none really exist.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] The illusion of geographic borders is due to the existence of patterns within the dataset rather than the visualization technique.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] The figure on the right displaying a heat map of world population also contains this occurrence.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Areas in rural parts of the United States and South America may closely resemble familiar geographic borders in those regions.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] Another example of a heatmap over a geographic area is a visualization of lake effect snow around Buffalo, New York, in mid-October 2006.
[src:heatmap-viz/heat-map] This figure shows another usage of heat maps with geographic areas, and how useful they can be in showcasing the effects of weather on specific areas as opposed to countries or states.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] In computer science, a **lookup table** (**LUT**) is an array that replaces runtime computation of a mathematical function with a simpler array indexing operation, in a process termed as ***direct addressing***.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] The savings in processing time can be significant, because retrieving a value from memory is often faster than carrying out an "expensive" computation or input/output operation.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] The tables may be precalculated and stored in static program storage, calculated (or "pre-fetched") as part of a program's initialization phase (*memoization*), or even stored in hardware in application-specific platforms.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] Lookup tables are also used extensively to validate input values by matching against a list of valid (or invalid) items in an array and, in some programming languages, may include pointer functions (or offsets to labels) to process the matching input.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] FPGAs also make extensive use of reconfigurable, hardware-implemented, lookup tables to provide programmable hardware functionality.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] LUTs differ from hash tables in that, to retrieve a value v with key k , a hash table would store the value v in the slot $h(k)$ where h is a hash function i.e. k is used to compute the slot, while in the case of LUT, the value v is stored in slot k , thus directly addressable.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] Before the advent of computers, lookup tables of values were used to speed up hand calculations of complex functions, such as in trigonometry, logarithms, and statistical density functions.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] In ancient (499 AD) India, Aryabhata created one of the first sine tables, which he encoded in a Sanskrit-letter-based number system.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] Early in the history of computers, input/output operations were particularly slow – even in comparison to processor speeds of the time.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] It made sense to reduce expensive read operations by a form of manual caching by creating either static lookup tables (embedded in the program) or dynamic prefetched arrays to contain only the most commonly occurring data items.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] Despite the introduction of systemwide caching that now automates this process, application level lookup tables can still improve performance for data items that rarely, if ever, change.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] Lookup tables were one of the earliest functionalities implemented in computer spreadsheets, with the initial version of VisiCalc (1979) including a `LOOKUP` function among its original 20 functions.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] Microsoft Excel includes multiple specialized lookup functions, with `VLOOKUP` for vertical lookup (as in a traditional lookup book), `HLOOKUP` for horizontal lookup, and (since 2019) `XLOOKUP` for outputting multiple output columns at once.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] Although the performance of an LUT is a guaranteed $O(1)$ for a lookup operation, no two entities or values can have the same key k .
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] When the size of universe U —where the keys are drawn—is large, it might be impractical or impossible to be stored in memory.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] For a trivial hash function lookup, the unsigned raw data value is used *directly* as an index to a one-dimensional table to extract a result.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] For small ranges, this can be amongst the fastest lookup, even exceeding binary search speed with zero branches and executing in constant time.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] One discrete problem that is expensive to solve on many computers is that of counting the number of bits that are set to 1 in a (binary) number, sometimes called the *population function*.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] For example, the decimal number "37" is "00100101" in binary, so it contains three bits that are set to binary "1".
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] The above implementation requires 32 operations for an evaluation of a 32-bit value, which can potentially take several clock cycles due to branching.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] It can be "unrolled" into a lookup table which in turn uses trivial hash function for better performance.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] The bits array, *bits_set* with 256 entries is constructed by giving the number of one bits set in each possible byte value (e.g.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] Sum of ones in each byte of the integer can be calculated through trivial hash function lookup on each byte; thus, effectively avoiding branches resulting in considerable improvement in performance.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] In data analysis applications, such as image processing, a lookup table (LUT) can be used to transform the input data into a more desirable output format.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] For example, a grayscale picture of the planet Saturn could be transformed into a color image to emphasize the differences in its rings.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] In image processing, lookup tables are often called **LUT**s (or 3DLUT), and give an output value for each of a range of index values.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] One common LUT, called the *colormap* or *palette*, is used to determine the colors and intensity values with which a particular image will be displayed.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] In computed tomography, "windowing" refers to a related concept for determining how to display the intensity of measured radiation.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] A classic example of reducing run-time computations using lookup tables is to obtain the result of a trigonometry calculation, such as the sine of a value.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] Calculating trigonometric functions can substantially slow a computing application.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] The same application can finish much sooner when it first precalculates the sine of a number of values, for example for each whole number of degrees (The table can be defined as static variables at compile time, reducing repeated run time costs).
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] When the program requires the sine of a value, it can use the lookup table to retrieve the closest sine value from a memory address, and may also interpolate to the sine of the desired value, instead of calculating by mathematical formula.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] Lookup tables can thus be used by mathematics coprocessors in computer systems.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] An error in a lookup table was responsible for Intel's infamous floating-point divide bug.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] Functions of a single variable (such as sine and cosine) may be implemented by a simple array.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] Functions involving two or more variables require multidimensional array indexing techniques.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] The latter case may thus employ a two-dimensional array of **power[x][y]** to replace a function to calculate **xy** for a limited range of x and y values.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] Functions that have more than one result may be implemented with lookup tables that are arrays of structures.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] As mentioned, there are intermediate solutions that use tables in combination with a small amount of computation, often using interpolation.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] Pre-calculation combined with interpolation can produce higher accuracy for values that fall between two precomputed values.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] This technique requires slightly more time to be performed but can greatly enhance accuracy in applications that require it.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] Depending on the values being precomputed, precomputation with interpolation can also be used to shrink the lookup table size while maintaining accuracy.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] While often effective, employing a lookup table may nevertheless result in a severe penalty if the computation that the LUT replaces is relatively simple.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] Memory retrieval time and the complexity of memory requirements can increase application operation time and system complexity relative to what would be required by straight formula computation.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] The possibility of polluting the cache may also become a problem.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] Table accesses for large tables will almost certainly cause a cache miss.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] This phenomenon is increasingly becoming an issue as processors outpace memory.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] A similar issue appears in rematerialization, a compiler optimization.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] In some environments, such as the Java programming language, table lookups can be even more expensive due to mandatory bounds-checking involving an additional comparison and branch for each lookup.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] There are two fundamental limitations on when it is possible to construct a lookup table for a required operation.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] One is the amount of memory that is available: one cannot construct a lookup table larger than the space available for the table, although it is possible to construct disk-based lookup tables at the expense of lookup time.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] The other is the time required to compute the table values in the first instance; although this usually needs to be done only once, if it takes a prohibitively long time, it may make the use of a lookup table an inappropriate solution.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] As previously stated however, tables can be statically defined in many cases.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] Most computers only perform basic arithmetic operations and cannot directly calculate the sine of a given value.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] However, this can be expensive to compute, especially on slow processors, and there are many applications, particularly in traditional computer graphics, that need to compute many thousands of sine values every second.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] A common solution is to initially compute the sine of many evenly distributed values, and then to find the sine of *x* we choose the sine of the value closest to *x* through array indexing operation.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] This will be close to the correct value because sine is a continuous function with a bounded rate of change.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] Unfortunately, the table requires quite a bit of space: if IEEE double-precision floating-point numbers are used, over 16,000 bytes would be required.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] We can use fewer samples, but then our precision will significantly worsen.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] One good solution is linear interpolation, which draws a line between the two points in the table on either side of the value and locates the answer on that line.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] This is still quick to compute, and much more accurate for smooth functions such as the sine function.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] Linear interpolation provides for an interpolated function that is continuous, but will not, in general, have continuous derivatives.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] For smoother interpolation of table lookup that is continuous **and** has continuous first derivative, one should use the cubic Hermite spline.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] When using interpolation, the size of the lookup table can be reduced by using *nonuniform sampling*, which means that where the function is close to straight, we use few sample points, while where it changes value quickly we use more sample points to keep the approximation close to the real curve.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] For more information, see interpolation.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] Storage caches (including disk caches for files, or processor caches for either code or data) work also like a lookup table.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] A single (fast) lookup is performed to read the tag in the lookup table at the index specified by the lowest bits of the desired external storage address, and to determine if the memory address is hit by the cache.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] When a hit is found, no access to external memory is needed (except for write operations, where the cached value may need to be updated asynchronously to the slower memory after some time, or if the position in the cache must be replaced to cache another address).
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] In digital logic, a lookup table can be implemented with a multiplexer whose select lines are driven by the address signal and whose inputs are the values of the elements contained in the array.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] These values can either be hard-wired, as in an ASIC whose purpose is specific to a function, or provided by D latches which allow for configurable values.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] An *n*-bit LUT can encode any *n*-input Boolean function by storing the truth table of the function in the LUT.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] This is an efficient way of encoding Boolean logic functions, and LUTs with 4-6 bits of input are in fact the key component of modern field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs) which provide reconfigurable hardware logic capabilities.
[src:heatmap-viz/lookup-table] In some systems, polynomials may also be defined in place of lookup tables for these calculations.
